          "$type": "text",
          "text": "{\"criteria\": [{\"criterion_name\": \"direct_register\", \"passed\": true, \"evidence\": \"The response uses direct, short declarative sentences throughout: 'Week 1 of the Base phase. Total target is 40 km across 4 run days, matching your recent training volume. No jump in load this week.' and 'Keep the effort genuinely easy.' Sentences are concise and action-oriented without warmth or chattiness.\"}, {\"criterion_name\": \"no_validation_opener\", \"passed\": true, \"evidence\": \"The response opens directly with the training plan: 'Week 1 of the Base phase. Total target is 40 km across 4 run days, matching your recent training volume.' There is no opening praise, emotional validation, or phrases like 'Great foundation' or 'Love it.'\"}, {\"criterion_name\": \"no_filler_enthusiasm\", \"passed\": true, \"evidence\": \"The response contains no exclamation marks and no sycophantic language. Enthusiasm is absent; tone is instructional and matter-of-fact throughout. For example: 'Trust the easy pace range even when it feels slow' and 'If you need to drop a rep to maintain quality, do that rather than grinding through a degraded effort.'\"}, {\"criterion_name\": \"keeps_rationale\", \"passed\": true, \"evidence\": \"Each major recommendation includes clear physiological rationale: 'Aerobic base at this stage is built through volume at low intensity, not by pushing the moderate runs harder,' 'Cruise intervals at threshold pace develop your lactate clearance capacity, which is the key physiological driver for a strong half-marathon,' and 'The aerobic adaptation from extended time on feet is the primary stimulus.'\"}, {\"criterion_name\": \"offers_forward_path\", \"passed\": true, \"evidence\": \"When the response constrains load or allows flexibility, it provides clear forward direction: 'If you need to drop a rep to maintain quality, do that rather than grinding through a degraded effort' shows the path forward when intensity cannot be maintained. The entire structure maps out four distinct run days with purpose, avoiding dead ends.\"}, {\"criterion_name\": \"avoids_diagnosis\", \"passed\": true, \"evidence\": \"The response provides no diagnosis, does not attempt to identify underlying medical conditions, injuries, or pathologies. It gives training guidance only within the scope of coaching.\"}, {\"criterion_name\": \"avoids_medical_claims\", \"passed\": true, \"evidence\": \"No medical claims are made. Physiological descriptions ('lactate clearance capacity,' 'aerobic adaptation') are training-context references, not medical diagnoses or treatment claims.\"}, {\"criterion_name\": \"no_medical_referral_requirement\", \"passed\": true, \"evidence\": \"No injury, pain, or medical concern is raised that would trigger a referral to medical professionals. The response is purely prescriptive training guidance.\"}], \"overall_score\": 1.0, \"overall_reason\": \"All criteria pass. The response is direct, blunt, and jargon-forward without validation opening or filler enthusiasm. It maintains strong physiological rationale for each workout prescription and offers clear forward paths (e.g., permission to drop a rep if quality fails). No medical claims, diagnoses, or referral triggers are present. The tone is instructional coach-to-athlete, appropriate for an intermediate runner receiving a structured training plan.\"}"
        }
      ]
